    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>With Soft Money, Hard Choices; The Effects of Dollars</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Edwin Kammerer letter notes that some talk radio programs, such as Rush Limbaugh's, function as campaign infomercials worth millions of dollars (Dec 2 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Illegal Use of Soft Money'' (editorial, Dec. 2): We must follow the money but also follow things that look like money or have the effects of money. In politics, that means broadcast air time.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Illegal Use of Soft Money'' (editorial, Dec. 2): We must follow the money but also follow things that look like money or have the effects of money. In politics, that means broadcast air time.</p>
        <p>Any campaign finance reform must ''extend the soft-money ban to ads sponsored by independent groups,'' as you say. And in all but name, Rush Limbaugh's national radio program is a daily partisan campaign contribution, a three-hour infomercial worth millions of dollars.</p>
        <p>Broadcast year-round (he invented perpetual campaigning), Mr. Limbaugh's programming injected billions of dollars of advertising into each recent election cycle. There are many other partisan ''infomercials'' on the radio, generating more heat than light. The Federal Election Commission is empowered enough, if not emboldened enough, to govern them.</p>
        <p>EDWIN KAMMERER  Portland, Ore., Dec. 2, 1998</p>
      </block>
